SIMPLE: occipital
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Occipital
<hw>Oc*cip"i*tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>occipital</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to
the occiput, or back part of the head, or to the occipital
bone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Occipital bone</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the bone
which forms the posterior segment of the skull and surrounds the great
foramen by which the spinal cord leaves the cranium. In the higher
vertebrates it is usually composed of four bones, which become
consolidated in the adult.</cd> -- <col><b>Occipital point</b></col>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the point of the occiput in the mesial plane
farthest from the ophryon.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Occipital</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Occipital
<hw>Oc*cip"i*tal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The
occipital bone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Occipito-</ent>⟦br⟧
